1 Introduction

The script extracts climatic data for populations in the clonal bank (CB) and their natural locations. Climatic data coming from ClimateDT are in two formats: point-based layers and raster data. For the populations origin areas, we used climatic data from the reference period (1901-1950) in raster format. For the CB in Spain, we used a specific time period corresponding to each phenotypic trait measurement. The periods are:
- Shoot Volume, stem long and spring elongation,Total open mature strobili (male): 1992-2012
- Leaf thickness: 1992-2021

2 Comparison point-based layer and raster data

Climatic data coming from ClimateDT are in two formats: point-based layers and raster data. For the clonal bank (CB) location, we used point-based data to obtain climate information over a specific period between the CBs establishment and the year of trait measurement. However, raster data, offering more climate models for future projections, was applied to analyze the range-wide dataset. This script aims to verify consistency between the point-based and raster data for CB populations to determine if raster data could be used to validate models built on point-based data.
For each traits, the climatic period is the year of establishment of the clonal bank (1992) to the latest year of trait measurement.
One key difference between raster and point-based data lies in their formats: - point-based data are available in one value per year for each variables (at each populations/pixel selected). - raster data are not so accurate, we have the average values over the selected period.

that bioclimatic (bio) and other climate variables are derived from monthly values of minimum temperature (tmin), maximum temperature (tmax), and precipitation. Therefore, to get an accurate mean for bio variables over a period (e.g., bio1 from 19011950), we must first average tmin, tmax, and precipitation for each month individually, resulting in one value for each month (January, February, etc.) over the period of interest. Using these monthly averages, we can then apply the biovars function from the Dismo R package to compute the 19 bioclimatic variables for the specified period (e.g., 19011950). For other climate variables like AHM over the same period, we can follow ClimateDTs protocol by incorporating the newly generated bio1, bio10, bio12, etc., values from biovars.

5 Comparison climate CB vs natural climate of populations

We can analyze the climate of the clonal bank (CB) in comparison to the populations to determine whether the CB represents an extreme environment relative to the populations. This investigation will help us understand the climatic differences and assess how they may influence the growth and phenotypic traits of the populations in the common garden.

Interpretation: The climatic range among the populations is significant, particularly regarding annual precipitation and temperature. For the clonal bank (CB), we observe that, compared to the other populations, the annual temperature is relatively high, especially during the driest quarter. Additionally, the temperature seasonality and diurnal temperature range are also important. Regarding the precipitations, the annual precipitations are quite low and the seasonal precipitations are following the mean value of the rest of the populations. These results suggest that the climate of the clonal bank (CB) could induce higher aridity constraints and greater temperature seasonality due to high annual temperature variability. This implies that adaptation to drought resistance and late growth/reproductive phenology could be advantageous in the climate of the CB because of the high temperatures during the driest period, low precipitation, and significant seasonal temperature fluctuations, which may lead to late frost events.
